The Telegraph - Calcutta : Metro

 The City Diary

 More than 30,000 families in the Bansdroni-Kudghat area had to go without water on Friday, as a 30-inch water main connected to the Bansdroni booster station, in Kudghat, sprang a leak. Chief engineer (water supply) Dibyendu Roychaudhury blamed the Metro Railway extension work for the leak. Supply to the area is likely to resume on Saturday morning.

 Chief minister Buddhadeb Bhattacharjee wrote to Prime Minister Manmohan Singh on Friday, expressing concern over the Centre?s decision to discontinue the Megacity project. A number of projects in and around the city could not be completed if the Centre stuck to its decision, Bhattacharjee wrote.

 A team from Bowbazar police station arrested 24 punters and seized Rs 40,000 in a series of raids on New CIT Road and its adjoining areas on Thursday night.

 A fire broke out at a house in Salt Lake?s AJ block on Friday, following an explosion in a cooking-gas cylinder. One tender was pressed into service. No one was injured. 

 One person died and 15 others fell ill after poisonous gas leaked from cylinders at a scrap iron workshop in Ghusuri, Howrah, on Friday evening. The injured were admitted to Howrah State General Hospital.

 Five men and two women were arrested on sleaze charges in Santoshpur on Friday. Police said the seven were picked up from a flat hired by a woman. All are in their twenties.

 Finance minister Asim Dasgupta underwent a minor surgery at SSKM Hospital on Thursday. Sources said the minister was recuperating satisfactorily. 

 A three-member team from Medical Council of India visited SSKM Hospital on Friday as part of the annual evaluation. The members inspected various departments related to the MBBS course. Admissions for the 2005 academic year can begin only after the medical council issues provisional registration to the hospital for the course. 

